  "title": "DISEC: A Skirmish Against Cyber Arms Trade",
  "content": "*When tyranny enters a nation, it is wrapped in the land’s cloth, carrying illicit arms in one hand in one hand and bashing minorities with the other*. Over the past hour, DISEC delegates have both grappled with the issue of the illicit arms trade on the dark web, and discussed issues and potential solutions. \n\nAs of the debate’s first hours, all delegations have been echoing the voice of Denmark and the US, who seek the removal of dark web media through a battle against cryptocurrency using the database and tools available to the International Criminal Police Organization (INTERPOL). Debate has remained intense, arguing methods shipment of arms, with nations such as Iran and Israel agreeing upon the need for stronger border security.\n\nEven though all nations unanimously agree to key issues, each nation has sought a separate path forward, with the delegation of New Zealand questioning the attack on cryptocurrency by quoting personal sovereignty. In response, the representative of Iran pressed the need for a repeal to the current dark web basis on anonymity laws, stating in **an exclusive interview** with Al Jazeera that anonymity “a privilege, not a right” that could be repealed if exploited, a statement echoed by the rest of the committee.  \n\nAs the debate begins to heat up, the committee has polarized into two unique blocks respective to their national interest. On one side, delegations from nations like the US and South Korea have grouped around the critical importance of tackling the issues of crypto, while on the other hand, delegates such as Russia, Iran, and New Zealand have been supporting each nation’s proposal. \n\nIn an interview with Iran’s vocal delegate, Iran disagreed with the issues of personal sovereignty raised by the US and believed that the US would be an issue moving forward. As the debate continues, a question still stands, will the discussion in the coming weekends help tackle the issues of the arms trade, or will it be another bust? \n",
