  "title": "Roaring Debates Take Place Inside the United States Senate  on Long-Awaited Adjustments to Affordable Healthcare ",
  "content": "*New York Times, April 2021*\n\nAs senators from all around the United States battle out their opinions on the failed doings of the Affordable Care Act (ACA), the demand for change rises. While affordable healthcare has been debated over the span of decades, the Senate notes minimal legislative progress. While the Republican senators believe the ACA has benefited the American population, Democratic senators, such as Bernie Sanders, tend to disagree.  \n\nSanders has stated his belief that the government should stop spending time on failed projects, such as the ACA, but rather focus on helping the current situation at hand with new ideas. Fellow democrat, Senator Chuck Schumer, has expressed that applying tax to health insurance would increase the number of people using it by creating competition between companies. Although both parties have many different views, both sides believe the government is in a very good position of influencing people's decisions about their healthcare plans. The people trust their government, therefore the government's responsibility is to address healthcare in an appropriate manner.\n\nOn the other hand, Senators have debated the implications of both the public and private health insurance systems. Senator of Rhode Island, Sheldon Whitehouse, likes the idea of further developing the public health care system due to its low cost and no deductibles. Ultimately the democratic Senators have continuously been voicing how an American citizen shouldn’t be choosing between having a decent healthcare system or putting food on the table. It has also been voiced how transparency to the citizens has been wanted for many years. Overall, people are angry and many do not have the luxury of healthcare. \n\nAs the flaming debates continue, the American people keep waiting. Although there are no doubts that the senators are trying to work together to solve this issue and develop more affordable healthcare plans, time is running out. \n",
