  "title": "Asylum Policy in Europe",
  "content": "Throughout this EU session, country delegates discuss the current asylum policy. Frontline nations such as Italy, Spain and Greece are feeling immense stress from the sheer amount of refugees entering their countries. These amicable nations are asking the EU for help with redirecting refugees in need to other nations better equipped to help. The strain of resources and money paired with the COVID-19 pandemic is often too much for these countries to deal with. Multiple other countries are offering their help through funding camps and transportation routes, although there is disagreement around focuses on either short-term transportation against long-term solutions such as relocation of camps. \n\nGermany is speaking on this topic, calling out financial problems as well as promoting the idea of camp relocations to countries who are able to maintain the best quality of life for refugees. However other countries such as Poland are attempting to bring the EU together and to redirect focus onto short-term solutions that can be attained in a timely manner. At the center of this discussion is the debate on whether improving the current refugee camps will ultimately be more effective than moving refugee camps as a whole. The Netherlands alongside Portugal are speaking on the effectiveness of these proposed short-term solutions and are pitted against Germany at the moment. France is asking for a compromise on this situation, focusing on both short and long-term solutions, making the solid point that refugees in current times would potentially be harmed by the decision to solely focus on the long-term. \n\nThe important topic of COVID-19 is also brought to light. As the world has been ravaged by the virus, the impacts on the lives of refugees has been immense. Because of the severity of the situation, frontline countries have doubts about accepting more refugees while worrying about the safety of their citizens. COVID-19 is making this conclusion all the more difficult for the EU to come to a unanimous solution as countries are concerned for the well-being of themselves and their fellow EU members. On this topic Germany comments on how countries may not have \"enough to spare\" on COVID-19 supplies and specialists. All countries who are affected by the pandemic are partial to these concerns, although no solid compromise have been reached at the moment of publication. Euronews appreciates the focus on this particular issue as we recognize the difficulties felt by the world in these difficult times. \n\nAs the session comes to a suspenseful close, countries continue to debate on the impacts of both options. The EU appears to be struggling to reach a conclusion that will be in the best interests of all countries at the moment. It is the hope of Euronews that these beneficent nations are able to reach a state of cooperation and are able to combine their want to improve the lives of refugees in need in order to bring forth a solution. ",
