  "title": "WHO discusses impacts of air pollution on chronic respiratory diseases",
  "content": "(CNN) – Upon settling on the topic of prevention of chronic respiratory diseases, the WHO delegates launched into a focused discussion of preventing CRDs in lower income countries. \n\nThe solutions proposed by the delegates are many: disease prevention systems, investment and financial aid lower income nations, research, and as Haiti bravely pioneered, the implementation of different gas systems in homes. The United States cited the matter as a “deeply ingrained issue that [must be] discuss[ed] now”, and diplomatically praises those speeches made by fellow member nations, but crucially proposes the “development of individual countries’ healthcare systems” to avoid dependence in consideration of the future and long term solutions.\n\nThe fruitful discussion became oddly interrupted by confusion over raised hands calling for a revote, and as hands often symbolize hospitality and generosity, wonderfully tying in with the lovely notions of member nations to mutually aid, develop and progress as a whole. The issue quickly passed, and once again the nations continued.\n\nTransitioning into the discussion of public awareness surrounding CRDs, expectedly the nations of the committee seem to be in consensus to improve facilities that promote public education, and pointed out many contributing factors to CRDs. A number of delegates seem keen on discussing tobacco and cigarette usage, and have consistently proposed moderated caucuses, as of the moment without success in gaining a majority to enter a focused discussion on the matter.\n\nThe dais encouraged delegates to look beyond a narrow scope and gauge the bigger picture. Perhaps more explicitly, other member nations have pointedly remarked in response that air pollution affects developing nations far more than that of tobacco and cigarette usage. Air pollution and smoking go hand in hand in terms of health risks, pointed out in the course of debate, and the smooth integration of the topics in a diplomatic, amiable fashion provided a satisfactory end for WHO’s first committee session. \n\n",
