  "title": "Traumatisation, Deception, and Abduction  - Tackling the Rise of Women in Terrorist Organisations",
  "content": "The economy is the backbone of any nation; social prosperity ensues. With illusory promises of a better economic and social status, women are forced down the path of violence and terror, seeing it as the only source of viable money. In regions, notably the Middle East, the roles of women are confined by ‘traditional’ values. Women often are restrained from receiving education, pressing them to choose terrorism as a method of income as they see no other path. As a result, they are unable to determine the true nature of these organisations and make decisions free of external influence. Furthermore, women are also subject to oppression within the household, carrying out domestic duties and serving their husbands. Hence, international efforts to eradicate terrorism failed to notice their utilisation, leading to approximately 10 per cent of recruits to the Islamic State being women. Nonetheless, their recruitment as suicide bombings and logistical operatives is still on the rise. Regardless of logistical roles in these terrorist organisations, women are subject to living horrors, notably sexual assault, forced marriage and childbirth, and even their selling to raise funds for further terrorist operations. \n\n\nNot only is the recruitment of women prevalent domestically, but terrorist organisations expand overseas to fulfil their international operations. Recently, numerous notorious female terrorists are native to Europe, choosing to flee their home countries to join Middle Eastern organisations. Nearly 550 women joined ISIS from Europe, and a further 60 joined the Al-Khansaa brigade. Several terrorist organisations use social media to spread their propaganda to Europe, spreading their radical ideology. It is well noted that every coin has two sides. Thus, despite the European Union’s efforts regulatory efforts, the right to privacy has hindered the EU’s actions to crack down on online terrorist recruitment.\n\n\nAs noted by Rwanda, creating domestic business incentives for women is a viable solution to fix the economic status of women in impoverished nations, which, in turn, lifts them from social poverty. Creating initiatives to promote cultural artisan crafts like knitting, weaving, and soap production will prove effective in the long run.\n\n\nRegardless, China is proud to have significantly decrease domestic terrorism regardless of gender. In historically separatist regions like Xinjiang, terrorism has virtually been eradicated for the past 20 years. Through government initiatives to promote skills and language education, potential separatists have found better alternatives to chaos. These efforts have led to increased GDP growth in the region as well.",
