  "title": "The IAC \"Debates\" (Without Clash) Indigenous Communities in Canada's Criminal Justice System",
  "content": "\n    \n   As we enter the first committee session in the Indigenous Advisory Committee, both the Dais and the delegates learn to work with a digital platform. Not once does the Chair forget to say “virtual hands” when asking delegates for points or motion. He hits his gavel to give the customary 10-second warning, and takes a moment to ask delegates if they can hear his gavel, just to confirm. \n\nHeading into the primary speaker's list, the two for two against, and secondary speakers list, delegates make speeches. The speeches were impressive indeed, so much so that we’re suspecting some of these delegates wrote these speeches beforehand; we’re sure this committee is full of knowledgeable and eloquent delegates, but does eloquence bring this many statistics, dates and references per speech? Regardless, the content and speeches in this committee have been impressive and informative.  \n\nThe IAC decides to discuss the topic of indigenous communities in Canada's criminal justice system first. Delegates first bring up issues with the status quo of the Indigenous communities and the justice system’s interaction. They bring up valid issues of overrepresentation in justice systems and police brutality. Nuances such as intergenerational trauma and colonial influences are acknowledged, and solutions such as restorative justice, and especially legal independence begin to be discussed. Delegates begin to develop their ideas regarding solutions, and discussing details and mechanisms of their solutions. We hear of plans to consult different first nations for restorative justice, and what legal independence would look like. In fact, delegates are in such agreement with each other that we have seen absolutely zero conflict or disagreement. The phrase “I echo the sentiments of the delegate before me” and “I agree with the previous points” are now customary at the beginning of every speech. \n\nAs the first committee session comes to a close, delegates are immersed in discussing and developing their solutions, we wish them luck in their next sessions! \n\n\n\n",
