  "title": "Members of SOCHUM Discuss and Try to Combat Child Labor ",
  "content": "Members of SOCHUM try urgently to combat child labour in developing countries even though it is only the first committee session. The delegates are already coming up with innovative solutions to combat child labour.\n\nIn this session, it seems that SOCHUM has voted to discuss Topic A (Child Labour in Developing Countries). Countries like the United States are already willing to work with other countries to end the horrible practise of child slavery in their countries.\n\nYet, before the delegates can develop more solutions, they must realise the root causes of child labour. In a moderated caucus on Root Causes of Child Labour, South Africa has stated that the leading cause of child labour is simple. Poor education and poor condition, forcing children to work instead of getting an education. Yet, Finland, one of the major contributors to countering child labour, believes that the leading cause is that since these kids have no money or education, the factories are abusing this and making the children work for money. It is evident that these two views are quite similar, so we hope that countries in SOCHUM will be able to corporate together.\n\nIn another moderated caucus on the Reintegration of Children in Society, the generous United Kingdom has stated that the best way to reintegrate children into society, these developing countries should make programmes. The United Kingdom has also stated they are willing to help fund these programmes as in the end, “children will be and are the future.”\n\nThe dais has constantly tried to get those countries that have spoken less to express their ideas and solutions. The committee members are already saying their solutions and communicating with other countries they agree with and are willing to work together with.\n\nThe members of SOCHUM seem confident in their ability to combat child labour and are not hesitant in expressing their ideas. Members have already come up with solutions such as creating a better education system and promoting specific organisations to help fund essential infrastructure. The passion the delegates have in this conference will enable the combat against child labour in the future.\n",
