  "title": "America Takes Lead in Denouncing Chinese Financial Exploitation",
  "content": "In an energetic start to the conference, many of the delegates of NATO found common ground on their stances against China’s exploitation of smaller nations. In fighting for worldwide economic justice, the American delegate brought forth recent demonstrations of Chinese immorality such as their false claims to the Philippines’ Whitsun Reef and the Iran-China deal, both of which grant China access to strategic sects of the globe. Delegates were quick to join America’s bloc, occasionally offering their own histories with Chinese debt-trapping and investment. The delegate of the United States emerged as a leader of this bloc, warning other delegates of the nation’s devious intentions and aggressive actions.\n\nHowever, a few delegates remained skeptical of these attacks on Xi’s regime. In one particularly heated caucus, the delegate of Montenegro sympathized with the Chinese government, accusing the Sri Lankan government of being “corrupt” and “irresponsible” despite them accumulating crippling amounts of debt from unwanted Chinese infrastructure projects. The American delegate refuted this narrative, reminding the committee to not conflate a nation’s poor financial situation with corruption—to not conflate unjust circumstances with a lack of ethics.\n\nThe German delegate elaborated on America’s defense of smaller nations, suggesting that the root cause of malicious Chinese expansionism is the lack of consequences they face for crimes—events such as the Uyghur genocide were brought forth by others in response to this bold idea. Furthermore, Germany suggests that NATO establishes command centers to unify and expedite NATO’s decisions surrounding the protection of smaller nations from Chinese exploitation. As the first committee session ended, ally nations expressed their support for this popular idea. The future of the fight against China’s hostile schemes looks bright for the committee.\n",
