  "title": "ASEAN Grapples With Rising Sea Levels ",
  "content": "Out of the ten recognized Southeastern Asian nations, none have yet made tangible progress on the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). Designed to mandate progress on seventeen climate action measures, the goals’ 2030 deadline looms over the sinking region. Let no mistake be made: panic has set in. Scientists have projected that by 2050, hundreds of coastal cities will be lost and millions of people are at risk of imminent destruction. With the majority of these communities being located in developing countries, this issue disproportionately affects Southeast Asian nations, which are also characterized as being low to the ocean and prone to natural disasters such as tsunamis, typhoons, and flash flooding.\n\nAt today’s session of the Canadian High Schools Model United Nations (CAHSMUN) conference, delegates from Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore urged each other to take dynamic action. Alarmed by the impending submersion of South Asian trade capitals Bangkok, Jakarta, Ho Chi Minh City, and Manila, each nation proposed a plethora of equally pragmatic actions to be taken by the others. Unfortunately, the three nations all failed to acknowledge the elephant in the room: who will offer their resources to help their cause?  \n\nJust as most United Nations (UN) detractors often stress, the body has never struggled to suggest a wide array of feasible and economically considerate approaches; nay, the UN’s shortcomings are not due to its resolutions but rather to its members. It is time for these enthusiastic nations to take a page from the book of an average toddler and learn to not bite off more than they can chew. \n\nIn the western hemisphere, us Canadians are not exempt from this crisis. Eminent climate researchers predict that Metro Vancouver will closely resemble the ancient city of Atlantis if dynamic remedial action is not taken by 2030. While Canada ranks thirteenth in the world by measure of SDG progress, we still fall drastically behind where we need to be. For the sake of millions of coastal Canadians, we have a long way to go.\n\nThe CAHSMUN conference will resume this discussion on Saturday and Sunday. At The Globe and Mail, we are eager to report on the resolutions made to combat this environmental, social, and economic crisis, and will update readers as soon as we can. \n",
  "author": "globeandmail",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T02:56:02.984Z"
  },
  "__v": 0
