  "title": "Rehabilitation versus Punishment: ILO on Prison Labor (Opinion Piece Included)",
  "content": "(CNN) – Ethics and morality regarding prisoner labor remains an ambiguous matter, the line between reformation and cruelty often blurring within complex prison systems. \n\nAmid discussion Finland provided an excellent point: “the purpose of prison is to prevent crime”, which should remain at the forefront of the mind whilst discussing the matter. The United States stresses the positives of prison labor, citing that prisoners who voluntarily participate have much to gain from the experience. The congregation seemingly is in agreeance to retain aspects of the prison labor system, with improvements. With this development, delegates enter a focused discussion regarding minimum wage for prison labor, the definition of fair compensation in such scenarios sparking speeches mirroring contrasting viewpoints whether prisoners should receive the same minimum wage as non incarcerated individuals or less than that value.\n\n(Opinion) - The criminal justice system exists to punish transgressions and strives for general improvement of society, and those convicted of criminal charges face lifelong obstacles in regards to employment, which severely impacts economic growth in countries with a high percentage of the population having criminal records. In regards to minimum wage in prisons, setting such a standard across the international community would be an enormously strenuous operation with many factors being unpredictable and not under the jurisdiction of the organization. \n\nCurrency values differ by country, and naturally, the differences in prison structure and management exist not only across nations but also internally, an example being private prison establishments, and these institutions have different interactions with government as opposed to federal prison institutions. While the encouragement and recommendation from the ILO to government systems, prison structures and the general public of wages in prison labor being around a certain value is plausible, without a means to enforce such regulations on an international scale, such notions may prove too idealistic to prevail long-term. The successes of the committee will solely depend on the willingness of delegates to compromise, implement and hold true the agreements made by the whole.\n",
  "author": "cnn",
