  "title": "UNEP: A Committee In Melting With The Heat Of The Debate",
  "content": "In the words of Benjamin Franklin, “When the well is dry, we'll know the worth of water.” This sentiment was present in the cheerful environment set forth by the dais in the UNEP, as a critical issue was put forth: “how can we progress waste management methods to protect our oceans?” \n\nAt the dawn of the debate, all delegates pressed the need for online waste management methods, with the Philippines amplifying the issue of less fortunate nations receiving the waste of the superpowers. This point drove the need for legislation for such management to the top of the agenda, as delegates echoed the all too common financial need sentiment. To add to the debate, a key point was brought forth by Korea’s delegate, who pressed the need for corporate responsibility, with Saudi Arabia presenting a global clean-up committee as a solution to the issue. \n\nIn contrast to these beliefs, Haiti accused capitalism’s structure as the primary source of the issues, stating that sovereignty is a source of pollution, with Russia also bashing the west for its actions in the matter. As an extension to the polarized committee, Brazil’s representative questioned the legitimacy of global warming, bashing the West for attempting to undermine its economy. In an exclusive interview, the delegate quoted the aid proposed during the amazon fire by the “global superpowers” as an example of the West’s ability to colonize developing states, insulting their sovereignty.\n\nAs the debate begins to heat up, the committee has forged two polar panels, with the West’s moderates taking the traditional pressing for change approach, while hardliners from Russia, Brazil, and Haiti press for the West’s true motives. Hope is all that's left for compromise and peace.\n\n",
