  "title": "The Role of Women in Terrorist Organizations and How it’s Being Handled ",
  "content": "UN Women, an organization in the United Nations is committed to preserving women's rights and providing further female empowerment. Over the course of a couple days, international countries have been arguing over women's roles in terrorist organizations and militias. Not only have they acknowledged the problem at hand but tried to look at the root causes which cause women to get persuaded to join these organizations. \n\n\tMany factors go into these persuasions, common ones such as:\n- Abuse - mostly from spouses\n- Trauma - childhood trauma and neglect \n- Previous directed violence - women that have been in many violent situations \n- False ideologies - false promises from terrorist organizations in order to grasp women's attention \n\nAlthough being involved in a terrorist operation is acknowledged as a horribly wrong thing, we forget to recognize how these individuals originally get involved in such actions. Finding these causes would not only help us understand their situation better but help these women get back up on their feet before they are introduced to any of these dangerous ideologies. \n\nAs the country's have been collaborating, many fresh ideas have sparked. Norway has expressed the importance of gender based research programs. They explain how this would help governments see where the specific problems are and have more knowledge on how gender affects persuasion tactics. Government studies are important but so is education for the ones affected. Though it’s  a good strategy we have to keep in mind that, still today, many countries limit, if not, do not have any education system catered to women. These education opportunities would cover how to stay smart and safe when it comes to coping with past traumas and how not to fall into terrorist traps. Countries would also have to align these programs with their peoples beliefs while making sure they spread the knowledge. The United States of America has also mentioned another possible  female run program that would help already affected women with support and guidance on how to continue on with their lives after being involved in terrorist organizations. This would include support groups and allow women to have job opportunities once again. \n\nIt’s most certainly comforting to know that countries are taking initiative towards un-talked about issues such as this one. This stigma of uncomfort around the subject has to be broken in order to permanently fix the problem.\n\n",
