  "title": "Child Labour in Developing Countries: The Next Step",
  "content": "Members in SOCHUM are creating alliances and presenting solutions - many of which clash - to combat child labour.\n\nAfter the delegates have stated their positions on the topic in the first session, delegates are now already getting into an intense debate in finding a solution. The delegates believe that before they can take action on the current situation, the child labourers must be first rescued from whatever labour they were forced or brought into.\n\nThe delegates are now presenting solutions. The most controversial solutions brought up include: rehabilitation programs, investment in education systems, and consumer awareness. \n\nWhile some countries believe the best way the help combat child labour is to ameliorate school curriculum, other countries certainly believe this is not the case. Delegates such as Switzerland’s delegation believe that the parents in these families are unwilling to cooperate, as they believe their children should help earn money for the family.\n\nAnother controversial topic currently being debated is rehabilitation programs. More prominent countries in the committee believe it would be a good idea to place these rehabilitation programs to help these children reform and prepare them for the future. These countries are also willing to help fund rehabilitation programs. Small and developing countries believe that this is nearly impossible as they believe the parents would disagree.\n\nSerbia believes that the reason why child labour is so popular is that so many people buy their products. Serbia’s solution to this is to “label these items with stickers so that when people buy them, they are warned, which may cause fewer people to buy these products. This ultimately causes these factories where children are working to shut down.” On the other hand, delegate of Canada has stated that “it is nearly impossible to stick a label on almost all the products. This also does no good as people will see it, but only a small amount of people will either truly care about or understand child labour.”\n\nAs time is closing in on them, and the debate is becoming more heated than ever, we anticipate that these nations will create comprehensive solutions, should they choose to collaborate. \n",
