  "title": "Facebook Revived? New Ideas Discussed in Most Recent Meeting ",
  "content": "    Facebook has been facing accusations of data breaches for years. As a result, their reputation has been dismantled, and company workers are struggling to brainstorm strategies to increase user activity. Will they be able to reach a successful conclusion? New developments suggest that they may. We at Euronews have investigated behind the scenes to bring you the most recent information currently unavailable to the public. \n\n    The company is currently divided into two different groups based on the idea of whether the product or platform is of more importance.\n\n    Sheryl Sandburg, the Chief Operating Officer of Facebook suggests that Facebook expands its horizons into a new company almost as a refresher for the public. Peter Thiel, the first outside investor in the company, suggests that Facebook branches out to create more apps which seems to be the general opinion expressed, however the topic and content of said app is being currently debated, but the topic of WeWork has been brought up in discussion. \n\n    WeWork is a company that allows one to quickly and easily find accessible office spaces. Peter Thiel is advocating to create a similar app. He believes that with higher technology and the assimilation of Facebook's initial social communication, the company can build an entirely new app. With the aid of Facebook's previous popularity, he says \"we will be more successful\" than WeWork is currently. However taking into account the scandals Facebook has been involved in, Euronews is curious to see how this situation develops. This is only one side of the company's story. \n\n    The other half of the company is proposing 3 different ways to expand the user base. Robert Kimmitt, the lead independent director of Facebook gave Euronews a basic summary of ideas previously discussed. He wants to firstly expand Facebook geographically, \"targeting areas such as Indonesia\" who many not have large access to the platform. This will be a strategic move on the companies' part. The second point he kindly brought up was integration. He calls for \"product over platform\": he wants to ensure that users embrace Facebook's social culture of status updates and posts. Lastly, Facebook wants to expand interest in the product for younger ages. Currently, Facebook is seen by the younger generations as a figment of the past, and by changing this, Facebook will recover and regain popularity. \n\n    Now these two groups have congregated. As both groups share their views on the future of the company, a clear difference in opinions has been uncovered. The idea of \"product over platform\" is pitted against \"platform over product\" and spurs discussions across the company board. So far, interesting developments have revealed themselves. It appears that both sides of the company are interested in developing their platform further through reaching out to a larger audience, but the difference of opinions from individuals is seemingly preventing the majority of potential progress. Euronews is curious to see how these developments will progress in the future. ",
  "author": "euronews",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T16:36:44.925Z"
  },
