  "title": "America and Allies in DISEC Do Not Negotiate with Dark Web Terrorists",
  "content": "In a stunning demonstration of American values, the delegate of America firmly rejected the notion of employing hackers—convicted criminals—to combat criminal activity on the Dark Web. A majority of the committee stood with America on this issue, offering their own comparisons of the efficacies of white-hat and black-hat hackers.\n\nThe American delegate, in a compassionate and wholly American act of diplomacy, also took into consideration the beliefs of opposing parties, suggesting that if criminal hackers were to be employed, strict regulations would need to be put in place to ensure their efficacy and loyalty. For self-evident reasons, we do not consider this negotiation with terrorists; anyone that believes otherwise stands against America and its mission of world prosperity.\n\nIn a separate caucus, America led the charge on discussing the formation of an international database on Dark Web activity. The advantages of this course of action are numerous; it would allow for DISEC nations to more easily coordinate actions against the shipping of illicit materials across the world.\n\nThe delegates of North Korea and Russia doubted the plans America had presented. The former delegate was blind to the evident value of creating a database, arguing that the database itself could be hacked by dark web criminals, and the latter delegate opposed the idea of transparency surrounding the movement of arms. It is worth noting that North Korea heavily restricts its citizens access to the internet—a violation of freedom of expression—and that much information about the Russian government’s arms movements is hidden from the international community. It appears that these two nations reject America’s strides to establish an international Dark Web database not to find an alternative path to global cybersecurity, but to fulfill ulterior motives. Seeing that the detractors of the delegate of the United States have yet to establish their credibility in their committee, it is likely that in future sessions, the delegates of DISEC will find a way to combat Dark Web criminality with effective American values.",
