  "title": "ChairMUN offline, EU Chair Counts Down on His Fingers for Delegates Debating Asylum Policy",
  "content": "At 8:40 in the morning, the European Union starts off their third committee session. As the committee tries to open their first session of the day, the ChairMUN program seems to have stopped working. Taking initiative, the Dais team comes up with a way to run without ChairMUN. The director instructs delegates to raise their hands as usual to vote, and in the absence of ChairMUN, delegates switch places in zoom's gallery view as they raise and lower their hands. The Dais team now uses inventive solutions to moderate debate, such as typing motions in the chat, and giving 10-second warnings by counting down on their fingers. \n\nIn their debate and discussion of asylum policy, members of the EU clash with each other. There seems to be an agreement among some delegations: notably, France, Italy, and Poland, who is wearing a gaming headset, argue that EU nations should have an appropriate quota of refugees to take in, and if not, repercussions such as sanctions should follow. The delegations of Greece raises concerns with economic situations, making reference to their state of relative economic turmoil, and is reassured by delegates in support of the quota policy that quotas will be decided for each country based on their unique situations. Germany raises their own concerns with public opinion, saying that the internal conflict in the EU, which has obviously never happened before, will make the EU look weak. The delegation of Denmark - the only delegate with their zoom video off - firmly disagrees with the proposed quota policy. They seem very eager to discuss “balancing humanitarianism with national interests”. A delegate of an opposing stance asks for an opportunity to discuss during an unmoderated caucus, and is met with awkward silence. Are they away from their computer? \n\nDespite a lack of ChairMUN, a useful tool for moderating debate, keeping the committee organized, and timekeeping for delegates, almost like an American conference, the committee is able to come up with temporary solutions and continue with fruitful discussion.\n",
  "author": "theonion",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T16:59:06.800Z"
  },
