  "title": "The Never Ending Questions on the Funding in Developing Countries ",
  "content": "It is the year 2021 and developing nations still need our help. Sadly, many still don’t recognize or see this issue in the world but it’s growing larger everyday. The Social Cultural and Humanitarian Committee, which is a part of the UN, has recently been further discussing long term solutions. \n \nAlthough some countries are in much better shape than others, it’s still valid to recognize everyone's level of development. A topic the UN brought up is child labor. Child labour is a horrible thing happening still today but without it, many country’s economys would not be able to survive. The Kingdom of Denmark’s main concern is about the well being of children who have been victims of child labour. Therefore, they believe in the same component Iran has voiced time and time again. They believe funding should be directed into those specific economies to try and extinguish child labour once and for all.  Venezuela has also stated how they’re afraid governments may misuse the funds provided and instead they could create an international reliable body that can aid these countries. This would work in a form of  an international trust fund as brought up by the UK. \n\nCorruption is the main concern here. Many countries like Iran and Pakistan consider this very closely and are building ideas that would allow solutions to be executed safely. The way this could be a safe process is by having some sort of system where  countries report to and which monitors the progress and use of funds from governments. Ultimately, funding works differently in every nation therefore it’s hard to come to a consensus of all the world's major governments.\n\n   Although we are still battling this very significant issue, progress is definitely being made. Now that we finally recognize child labour is a major component for many econmies and a motive for many families, countries are able to progress and further develop their latest ideas. Implementing effective laws and a sense of stability for citizens is what’s vital in saving economies and possible child labour victims. \n",
  "author": "newyorktimes",
