  "title": "UNEP: Wind Of Change ",
  "content": "As the second day of debate resumed, technological difficulties brought an essential environmental committee to its feet, pleading for mercy. To fill up the time, the dais had an interesting debate about “breakfast burritos and sauce,” outlining the lack of progress in the deem committee.\n\nFollowing this fruitful intermission, the debate entered the secondary speakers’ list as a wave of voluntary response bias overtook the room, quieting all with neutral views. The delegation of Norway, Saudi Arabia, and Brazil echoed previous positions, all while stating they are open to compromise. Brazil further cemented its anti-west stance, quoting the lack of financial support as the true lack of care for developing states. Haiti echoed this sentiment by stating that the middle ground is critical moving forward, with countries working not as first or third world countries but instead as second world powers.\n\nTo re-establish key points in the debate, Singapore acknowledged that the ocean had become a “saucy soup of chemical waste,” stating that a one-size-fits-all solution is not a peaceful path forward. Yet, as agricultural and cosmetics waste overtakes the ocean, delegates continuously kept a seemingly calm face progressing forth with hope and blank words. \n\nIn an exclusive discussion with Saudi Arabia’s delegate, she pressed the critical need for global leaders to take the first step to pave the path for the rest of the world to follow. Saudi Arabia further questioned the global superpowers’ motives, as “they [were] the ones instigating the issues.” To add, the delegate pressed the importance of implementing the technology already available rather than spending critical resources on forging new ones. As the debate proceeds, it appears that humans are the only animals that foul their own nests.\n",
