  "title": "United States Senate on Affordable Healthcare: Featuring Exclusive Interview with Senator Bernie Sanders",
  "content": "(CNN) – Today the US Senate continues their discussion on affordable healthcare. Whilst discussing merits of different solutions, Senator Amy Klobuchar pointed out that the Senate has been able to come to a consensus on the need for more checks on pharmaceutical companies as an effort to reduce medication costs and increase transparency. The Democrats and Republicans differ in opinion on whether a universal healthcare system is too limiting, and thus diverge in how to proceed with the matter.\n \nSenator Bernie Sanders critically stresses the importance of  retaining and “expand[ing] Medicare” and “includ[ing] more Americans” to establish a long term solution. We requested an interview with Senator Sanders on the matters being discussed by the Senate, and he obliged to respond to our questions.\n \n(CNN) – What do you personally believe the definition of affordable healthcare is?\n \n(Sen. Bernie Sanders) – “I think that affordable healthcare is pretty self-explanatory – with millions uninsured in this nation…what we have at the moment is not affordable healthcare. The best way is the introduction of Medicare for all…I understand that based on political beliefs this may be difficult.”\n \n“I want to ensure that the healthcare bill we pass will extend healthcare and crack down on pharmaceutical companies…healthcare is something that should be affordable that people can actually pay for.”\n \n(CNN) – What goals does your party have regarding healthcare improvement?\n \n(Sen. Bernie Sanders) – “I think something that we were all able to agree on was that there needs to be an expansion of Obamacare and Medicare and the Obama reform act…so that is something I definitely think will be happening.”\n \n“Our goals are to increase coverage for American people, tackling pharmacare…ending surprise billing has been brought up a lot…essentially we want expansions on [our current systems] as we want more restrictions on pharmaceutical companies.”\n \n(CNN) – What strides are the Democratic Party making towards reaching your goals?\n \n(Sen. Bernie Sanders) – “Currently there are a couple bills in circulation: one of those is the React Act...[which plans] to take the existing infrastructure of Obamacare and Medicare and building on them for an increase in transparency and options available to the American people.”\n \n“What the Republicans were bringing up a lot was the possibility of an option that people are not forced into, and I can see where they are coming from. I think that the downfalls and shortcomings of having universal healthcare have been a little bit exaggerated, but what the Democratic Party has settled on is the React Act, and another bill written by Chuck Schumer that focuses more on the expansion of just Obamacare.”\n \n“Something we really have to work on right now is cementing our ideas as a party, and making sure we can come to agreement on one bill and pass that.”\n \n(CNN) – What do you anticipate the outcome of debate on this topic will be for your committee as a whole?\n \n(Sen. Bernie Sanders) – “I think when it comes to the affordable healthcare topic, there has been a bit of overlap between what Democrats and Republicans are pushing.”\n \n“Republicans are looking for repeals on Obamacare, and Democrats are looking for expansion on Obamacare and Medicare, so that is where [the parties] differ. But I think one thing everyone has been able to agree on is pharmaceutical companies, and the [overall] issue of big [pharmaceutical companies] overall.”\n \n“I think that were is absolutely, one hundred percent going to be more restrictions on pharmaceutical companies to reduce the cost of prescription companies and medication for the American people.”\n \n“I have definitely seen a lot of consensus on that, and then since there is a Democratic Party majority…and I do think some Republican senators will be able to get behind it.”\n \n“At the end of the day, you have a majority, so I do predict the expansion of Medicare and Obamacare by the end of today.”\n \nCNN would like to thank Senator Bernie Sanders for joining us. While political parties and more radical concepts tend to influence such decisions - thus causing division and unsatisfactory results for many American citizens - the consensus of the Senate on doing the best for the people is encouraging and inspiring. CNN wishes the US Senate all the best in their endeavors to improve healthcare for the American people.\n",
