  "title": "SOCHUM Actually Productive and Inclusive for a Big Committee, Discussion on Child Labour Sounding Really Bad Out of Context",
  "content": "In the social, humanitarian, and cultural committee, a whopping fifty-one delegates discuss child labour in developing countries. Fifty-one is an impressive number for an online committee, given how difficult it can be to moderate debate and keep delegates on tasks in an online platform. Though moderating debate over Zoom can be difficult, the Dais is probably thankful for both Zoom's stellar audio quality, and the aspects of the platform that make pausing debate so delegates can form an awkward line at the podium, unnecessary. SOCHUM is running smoothly; nobody has tripped over projector wires. \n\nEven with such a large committee, a diverse selection of delegates are speaking, unlike usually in bigger committees, where the vast majority of delegates may as well not be there, many delegates are speaking on their stances and offering their solutions, and everyone has an opportunity to talk. In a committee without much major clash, there are few big debates between delegates, reducing periods of time where outsiders to the debate are denied chances to speak. Perhaps it’s less entertaining to watch arguments over an online platform. \n\nSOCHUM delegates, in their discussion about child labour in developing countries, continue to brainstorm concerns about types of exploitation, and possible solutions to the topic, including partnering with NGOs or introducing additional framework. The delegates are participating in a nuanced discussion on the difficulty of banning child labour and alternatives. \n\nWithout a doubt, these delegates mean well, and don’t actually support child labour, concerning phrases are thrown around, including “we shouldn’t outright ban child labour” (which sounds *very* concerning out of context). \n\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/2FvwFKy\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/QJPZJmf/Polkadots-Border-New-Year-Quotes.png\" alt=\"Polkadots-Border-New-Year-Quotes\" border=\"0\"></a>)\n\n",
