  "title": "UNSC: Conflict Between China and the United States Rises",
  "content": "**China is unwilling to corporate with the United States, while the United States believes that China’s CPEC program is a way to gain more influence in Balochistan.**\n\nChina has stated and expressed repeatedly that they are unwilling to work with the United States of America but are willing to work with every other nation.\n\nWith two out of five permanent members of the committee having internal conflicts, it was agreed upon in the second unmoderated caucus to give them a private breakout room to discuss the problem. Members from the BBC have received access to this discussion. China explained that, because India is one of the U.S.' allies, China does not want to work with the U.S. The U.S. has realized this and has backed down from working with China. \n\nYet, at the same time, the U.S. has repeatedly stated how China's primary agenda is simply to dominate global resources. Even after this discussion, the tension between the two still exists. The U.S. still has untrust towards China, calling the CPEC a “way to expand and get an economic gain.” The U.S. keeps bringing up how the CPEC will enable China to continue to expand its sphere of influence. \n\nSome nations have already leaned towards the west, while others have leaned towards the east. Vietnam has already tried to ease this tension. The delegate of Vietnam has explained how even if China has ulterior motives, the CPEC program will still help out the Balochistan people, reducing the pressure overall.\nFrance has encouraged other countries to stay neutral rather than take sides, trying their very best to reduce the tension at the moment.\n\nWith the fourth committee session closing in on the members in the UNSC, they must find a solution not only to this. They must find solutions to the Rojava Revolution as well as the Balochistan Conflict - and we here, at the British Broadcasting Corporation, wish them the best of luck. \n",
  "author": "bbc",
