  "title": "(OPINION) U.S. Politics: Amid Increased Support for Smokers, Opioid Harm Reduction a Far Cry from Reality",
  "content": "*Note: This piece is a submission from one of our readers and represents neither The Globe and Mail’s perspective or the individual perspectives of our editors, contracted writers, and patrons. *\n\nOn Saturday morning, delegates from all corners of the globe gathered at Vancouver’s Canadian High Schools Model United Nations (CAHSMUN) conference to reflect upon the health implications of air pollution, the COVID-19 pandemic, and smoking, with specific regard given to the steadily increasing prevalence of chronic respiratory diseases. \n\nFor reference, the term “chronic respiratory disease” refers to a multitude of debilitating health conditions targeting the human respiratory system, the most common of which are asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), cystic fibrosis, sleep apnea, and lung cancer. According to the Public Health Agency of Canada, an estimated 3 million Canadians suffer from a chronic respiratory disease, the majority of whom are habitual users of nicotine and/or tobacco products. These statistics are expected to be exacerbated by the COVID-19 pandemic’s adverse lung effects, however research data is still being collected and will likely be released towards the end of this year.\n\nToday’s youth, the generation tasked to end smoking once and for all, are failing miserably at learning from their parents’ mistakes. In 2019, Health Canada reported that 17.8% of high school students had admitted to “vaping” within the last month.  For our southern neighbours, that statistic was 20.8% (United States Bureau of Health). \n\nAt this weekend’s CAHSMUN conference, these statistics were of utmost importance. One of the key general assemblies at the conference’s 17th iteration, the World Health Organization (WHO) opted to split the topic and critique public health ideologies and their relevance to the youth vaping epidemic. Notably, the delegation of the United States (US) advocated for an unprecedented and out of character approach: harm reduction. \n\nElizabeth Jen, the delegate representing the global giant, stated that “The United States seeks to implement designated indoor spaces within schools where youth will have the opportunity to vape in privacy”. When asked if the same safety measures would be extended to people entrenched in drug abuse of higher severity, Jen was hesitant.\n\nIn Canada, various health measures (such as our ban on youth-targeted advertising for nicotine products) have been implemented for tobacco and/or nicotine focused harm reduction; the US has failed to demonstrate any evidence of past efforts to support individuals suffering in active addiction. Thus, skepticism of these lofty proposals is not unreasonable. \n\nAs with many American policy changes, this proven-positive strategy is set to reach those with a desperate need for life-saving support last. The hypocrisy of the US pushing the envelope for nicotine and/or tobacco harm reduction while still actively inflicting terror into the lives of opioid addicts is a textbook example of class privilege in one of the world’s top democracies.\n\nFrom a Canadian perspective, we still have a long way to go, however our social and political sympathy for schedule C drug users is undeniably higher than that of the US. For example, designed to support active addicts, opioid agonist therapy (OAT) is one of the cardinal examples of harm reduction policy. This therapy is enthusiastically used in Canada and yet is also criminalized in the majority of the US. \n\nUltimately, criticism of this dangerously selective policy change is warranted by both drug users and their allies. Canada and the United States must both counter the widespread misconception that e-cigarettes are a safe alternative to “the real deal”. Active anti-oppressive work must be done in order to redefine addiction as a health disorder that deserves treatment, no matter if the user’s drug of choice is a Marlboro Red or a brown baggie of heroin. \n",
  "author": "globeandmail",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T18:33:43.823Z"
  },
