  "title": "The On-Going Conflict Happening in Balochistan ",
  "content": "\tCivil wars have re-ignited in the Balochistan province of Pakistan.With these on-going conflicts which originally sparked in the late 1940’s , you'd think things would be peacefully resolved by now. Unfortunately, conflict re-appeared once again in 2005 after the captain of the national army raped Shazia Khalid. Shazia Khalid is a very well respected female doctor in the nation, therefore  this not only angered the public but caused them to lose all trust in their government and fully overturn back into a civil war statuts.\n\n\tThe United Nations Security Council has been working tirelessly to try and calm the current situation in Balochistan. Some of the main concerns brought up by countries would include people's lack of education and the exceedingly low literacy rate of 46%. \n\n*Why is education even being discussed here? Why is it relevant? \n*\n\tWe live in an age where knowledge is vital for the human kind to progress. It’s also important to note that education plays a significant role in national development. Therefore, with such a low literacy rate and lack of resources for education, Balochistan and its people are stuck in a continuous cycle of confusion, danger and violence. No educated or progressive government officials and no people with their own opinions but rather based on corruption ideologies,  leaves the nation stuck in time. \n\n\tMany countries also brought up their concern on electoral violence. Violent transfers of power or any dangerous activities caused by the new government further disrupt the peace of the nation. This makes citizens feel unheard and angry because of their own government. The only way the people of Balochistan feel they’ll be able to be noticed is by further rebellion and disruption. \n\t\n\tNow that this cycle has been recognized we are one step closer to permanent peace. Seeing the UNSC continuously collaborate and merge their disagreements into redirections and new solutions helps the people of Balochistan have hope for the nation's future. \n",
