  "title": "US Senate: Democrats On The Brink Of Collapse",
  "content": "    \nFree health for all; is that too much to ask? This question was tackled in the Senate today, as all parties wished for the same outcome, with unique paths of achieving solutions present; the Republicans pursuing an economically favourable path, while the democrats followed a course of health care for all.\n\nAs of now, the Democratic and Republican blocs have both agreed on the measure of accountability for Pharmaceutical companies for price transparency. The Democrats wished for a national price on medicine, with negotiations among insurance companies and pharmaceutical companies. The Republicans also demand that certain individuals get to override the need for payment, all while allowing for a special savings account directed at health care investment.\n\nSenator McConnel tackled the Democrats’ goal of excluding the FDA from imported drugs, forging a rumbling debate in the caucus. Tise issues set forth created a stiff skirmish among the senators, as the Democratic party entered a meltdown with their bill of loopholes. Senator Klobuchar pressed for unity and wished to pursue the broken bill; however, no successful results have been seen. \n\nSimultaneously, a rift has forged in the Senate through the Democrat’s demand for an expansion to Medicare for all, as the 32 trillion USD cost of the plan created a scapegoat for the Republican party to denounce the Democrats. As the debate elapsed, a key point was brought forth by Senator Sanders, who pressed the need for corporate responsibility, a view too extreme for the democrats.\n\nLike all bills before, it appears that the current one has the senate divided based on ideology and cost. The Republicans have stood their grounds on the high cost of the effective initiative, all while the Democrats have pressed medicare for necessary procedures. A question still stands, will this attempt for the most basic right to medicare lead to a bust or actual change?\n",
