  "title": "Indigenous Self-Governance in Canada: IAC Discusses the Criminal Justice System, Moves Forward with Resolutions",
  "content": "(CNN) – Complex logistics regarding self-governance has sparked much debate within the IAC in how to approach the matter. Sheila Watt-Cloutier cites that due to “diverse cultural backgrounds”, one single method to collectively use may be ineffective. Thus, the collective brought forth many individual ideas to aid the indigenous people in leading better lives through access to education, healthcare and equal opportunities.\n \nMumilaaq Qaqqaq spoke of bridging the “socioeconomic disparity between indigenous peoples and the rest of the population” through increased job opportunities. Lorraine Whitman points out the benefits of providing “a boost to education facilities” to provide funding for furthering education. Adam Olsen wants to “recognize the culture that exists in their everyday lives”, and provide aid while respecting these customs. Blocs “Swag” and “All Stars: Shrek” convened in smaller groups. “All Stars: Shrek” places great focus on restorative measures in the criminal justice system along with providing positive influences and resources for indigenous people while promoting connections between indigenous communities and the general government. “Swag” likewise discusses reform of the criminal justice system as well as improving the education system, legislation and bringing awareness to the matter.\n \nSheila Watt-Cloutier provided the following statement on behalf of “All Stars: Shrek”:\n \n“Our main goals are increasing Indigenous self-governance (both on reserves and in urban areas), improving socioeconomic conditions of Indigenous communities, decreasing unjust police violence, increasing Indigenous representation in justice system, and enhancing reconciliation as well as connections with [the] deferral government.”\n \nSylvia McAdam Saysewahum, from “Swag” additionally provided us with the following statement:\n \n“As Indigenous people face numerous injustices within the Canadian Criminal Justice System, my bloc’s primary goal is to reinstate Indigenous self-governing systems within Indigenous communities. Another goal is to increase Indigenous representation in the executive and judicial branches of the Canadian government, so as to reduce biases against Indigenous peoples. Finally, we are recommending adjustments to Canadian Curriculum to further include Indigenous history to educate the general Canadian population on Indigenous issues.”\n \nLiving up very much to their namesakes, blocs “Swag” and “All Stars: Shrek” have wonderfully approached the matter of self-governance with meaningful steps, and make positive strides towards passing effective resolutions. As a message to all delegates, we quote the wise words of the dais: “go outside, touch the grass, and we will see you in a little bit”. \n",
  "author": "cnn",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T19:43:19.069Z"
  },
