  "title": "Opinion Piece - How the EU Plans on Dealing with Asylum Seekers and Refugees",
  "content": "What happens when the current European Union Asylum Policy fails to do its job? It has caused countries in the EU to receive an overwhelming amount of refugees, and its delegates are trying to solve this problem. Ever since the 2000s, countries in the European Union have admitted an overwhelming number of refugees and asylum seekers, which has sparked much controversy. Many of these nations have already accepted many refugees, and most governments do not want to receive them anymore. \n\n<a href=\"https://imgbb.com/\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/jhcfhTj/download-2.jpg\" alt=\"download-2\" border=\"0\"></a>\n\nAlthough the EU has alloted ample monetary and physical resources to this cause, these refugees remain at-risk citizens of their new (or temporary) homelands. In the sober words of Poland, “we believe that we do not have enough materials to help these refugees... [and] there are many anti-refugee protests and sentiments in our country.” Not all countries would like to take in these refugees; once refugees are rejected from one nation, they continue to knock on other doors, and as a result, refugees are unable to settle.  \n\nAn idea that was brought up in the committee was by using quotas. Poland believed that refugees should be taken by countries with space rather than smaller countries, as these refugees would only get shunned by the citizens in these smaller countries. Yet, Italy posed this question: \"How low can countries set their quotas?...If countries can just set their [quotas] to [be disproportionately low], what would happen to the refugees who weren’t taken in?” \n\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/ch8dXTj\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/GQMj3Pq/54926357-101.jpg\" alt=\"54926357-101\" border=\"0\"></a><br />\n\nAs the BBC, we see both the beneficent and dangerous potential of quotas. We recognize that conservative current European citizens may celebrate the prospect that EU member states would lower their refugee intake. But we also recognize that the implementation of a massive quotas system will incentivize most other nations to follow suit, making meeting basic needs more difficult for all displaced persons. \n\nUltimately, after some modification of the ideas and solutions the EU has presented, we here at the British Broadcasting Corporation believe that they will solve this issue once and for all. \n",
  "author": "bbc",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T20:37:29.468Z"
  },
  "__v": 0
