  "title": "Opinion: DISEC’s Inimical Bonds Cause Superfluous Suggestions",
  "content": "*This article reflects the opinions of the author, not necessarily those of Xinhua.*\n\nFollowing the assassination of Qasem Soleimani, Iran-US relations hit an all-time low. Yet, through the spirit of cooperation amidst the pandemic, the two adversaries have interlocked fingers in a valiant effort to trump the dark web. To Xinhua’s shock, this arrangement fabricated some objectively *inclusive* proposals, including creating subcommittees, allocating funds, listing past UN resolutions, and finding *multifaceted* solutions. It is our professional opinion that their next all-encompassing solution would be ‘lifting people out of poverty’.\n\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/f0CyPMW\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/C0nYTBy/Screenshot-2021-04-10-at-1-27-50-PM.png\" alt=\"Screenshot-2021-04-10-at-1-27-50-PM\" border=\"0\">\n\nAnalogous to how the Trump administration pointed fingers at external factors for the mishandling of the COVID-19 pandemic, certain members of this committee are proud to present solutions in which they play no role. Some *beautifully* crafted proposals include placing responsibility on the International Criminal Police Organisation (INTERPOL) and the European Union Agency for Law Enforcement Cooperation (EUROPOL), having private firms be responsible for cybersecurity, holding UN training courses through certainly meaningful discussions, and creating subcommittees for other delegates to deliberate the matter. \n\nOne clause is worth noting that is definite: ‘Resolves to remain actively seized of the matter with zest’. Let’s hope through more meaningful discussions and targeted funding, DISEC can pull itself back on a track of triumphing its own confusion.",
  "author": "xinhua",
