  "title": "The Role of Women in Terrorism",
  "content": "    UN Women has been advocating for women's rights throughout this entire session. The specific topic at hand is women's roles in terrorist groups. So far, most member states have merged blocs in order to structure a detailed resolution paper which has just been passed. Euronews is pleased to see this progress and hopes for the continuation of this cooperation between delegates. \n\n    For a brief background on this topic, the committee is focusing on the recruitment of women into terrorist organizations, their roles, and the reasons behind their recruitments. Especially in rural areas or third-world countries, women are more likely to be recruited by terrorist groups. The majority of these women face relentless abuse from their superiors in the organization. UN Women is working quickly to find solutions in order to stop this cycle from continuing on and causing harm around the world. \n\n    The resolution paper's three most crucial points included providing as many vulnerable women with basic needs as possible, education against recruitment, and empowerment in communities. Euronews didn't catch the entirety of the session, but the information below is what we gathered. \n\nUN Women wishes to decrease poverty rates among women because having basic needs met reduces the likelihood of being recruited into terrorist organizations. The second point around the education against recruitment is straightforward: it endorses educating women, particularly in rural areas or third-world countries, about how to stay safe and the personal safety concerns associated with working in a terrorist organization. The third and final point is around empowering women in the system. This is quite possibly the hardest section of their paper to achieve, but Euronews has faith in the abilities of the tireless members of the UN Women's committee. ",
