  "title": "OP-ED: America’s Support of UNEP “ONCELER” Paper is a Symptom of a Weak-Spirited Biden Administration",
  "content": "*A correspondent of Fox News has received an early version of the working paper in the United Nations Environmental Program known as the “Ocean Non-Contamination Elected Leaders Embracing Reform” (abbreviated as “ONCELER”). The following is an opinion piece discussing it.*\n\n----------\n\n\n\nLet’s begin with the most jarring aspect of this working paper: its name, a nod to a Dr. Seuss book about an orange monkey who “speaks for the trees.” But trees are inanimate objects. Who will speak for those who need to be heard—the people?\n\nThis is the failure that I see in the ONCELER paper: the nations of the UNEP are assigning arbitrary hoops for themselves to jump through, diverting intelligence and resources away from living people and strong economies.\n\nPerhaps the saving grace of this paper is that most of it is non-binding. However, the regulations on oil, plastic, and other chemical wastes that it urges nations to impose on themselves would merely hinder the efficacy of American industry. It is also worth noting that President Trump, in repealing nearly one hundred environmental regulations during his term, was able to continue the growth of the American GDP, hinting at economic potential in environmental deregulation.\n\nBut the ONCELER is just a set of “recommendations,” so in return, I recommend that the Biden government forgoes them.\n\nEven if I were to buy into the mission of climate action that the ONCELER paper sets for itself, it would still fall short! The UN-sponsored ocean waste management exams and certifications it seeks to establish are empty virtue signals—only this time, on a global scale—and the “reverse vending machines” it proposes already exist in the form of plastic depots. Neither of these “solutions” have or will transport the world out of the dangers the UNEP deluded itself into seeing.\n\nDo I believe that humans have contributed to climate change? Maybe. But whether or not we have matters less to me than the fact that it is a naturally occurring phenomenon. None of the arbitrary restrictions outlined in the ONCELER paper will cause environmental change on the same order of magnitude as the forces of nature; they will only make it more complicated for industries—for working class Americans—to remain alive.\n",
  "author": "foxnews",
  "enabled": "true",
  "lastUpdated": {
    "$date": "2021-04-10T21:58:51.587Z"
  },
