  "title": "Facebook Working Concerningly Hard to be an Even Bigger Part of Your Life",
  "content": "In society, we have a general consensus that Facebook is very trustworthy, and we would love for it to expand into even more sectors of our lives. Luckily, the Facebook committee has some ideas.\n\nThe Facebook committee’s first topic is structured to be a case competition of sorts, delegations are to form blocs to make presentations of business ideas, and present them to judges.. The content of their presentations revolves around competition with Tencent. Blocs have come up with ideas for Facebook, such as new features, improvements on current features, and sectors that the company can invest and participate in. \n\nOne such case, presented by Rober Kimmitt, Mike Schroepfer, and Nancy Killefer, focuses on three main goals: expanding the user base, incorporating and nurturing a monetary system, and integrating more Facebook services into daily life. This case aims to target potential users that are in a younger age group, and potential users in Africa. This case encourages Facebook to start a PR campaign to attract more users. One of the two target audiences is younger people, who use Facebook less than older generations. The young, hip, cool zoomers don’t want to use a boring platform like Facebook, that’s for boomers. The PR campaign aims to change this view. The second of the case’s target audiences is African users. As neither Facebook nor Tencent services are particularly popular in Africa yet, this group encourages Facebook to take action and to trap African users in the Facebook ecosystem before competitors can trap said African users in their own. Their second big idea of a monetary system is made up of features such as Facebook pay™, rewarding loyal users with Facebook gift cards™ that can conveniently be deposited into Facebook accounts™ or spent on Facebook shops™, and give monetary incentives such as cashback, especially to those poor African countries that would jump at an opportunity for a social media and a payment system to take over their lives. Another main idea revolves around integration into daily lives, encouraging facebook to acquire companies and have stakes in even more sectors, and developing and introducing AR to daily life and social media. \n\nThe second case, presented by Mark “zucc” Zuckerberg, Antonio Lucio, and Sheryl Sandberg, had ideas just as creative. They detail areas of competition with Tencent as well, and present their own case. Again with three pillars, the case encourages Facebook to work on a payment system, and even hold capital and act as a bank, platform integration, and expansion into other sectors. The presenters acknowledge that Facebook has a steady and reliable growth in user base and in profit, but lacks innovation. Their first big idea, very similar to the first bloc, as capitalism breeds innovation, is of a payment system. The case encourages Facebook to partner with PayPal, an established payment method, to convince users that they can definitely trust facebook’s payment system, and should definitely abandon their banks and credit card companies for Facebook. The case ambitiously proposed that Facebook eventually develop into a bank and hold capital, so Facebook can now control both your social media and your money! Secondly, the case details a plan to increase platform integration; Mark Zuckerberg tells us that this would look like an extension on the Facebook app to offer features useful in everyday life, such as a way to download and read books, order food, read news, and even hire personal trainers all on Facebook. with this extension, you won’t need any other apps on your phone, and you can spend all your time and money on Facebook! This bloc, once again similar to the bloc before, is expanding into other sectors, specifically VR. Surprisingly unlike the previous bloc, this bloc singles out the gaming industry in particular, and focuses on more underdeveloped and unconventional sections, such as VR, AR, and Neuralink technologies. \n\nMaybe capitalism does breed innovation after all; Facebook delegates came up with some creative, innovative, and concerningly invasive ideas to broaden Facebook’s reach even more. With these amazing ideas, not only will Facebook know all of your information and interests, it can bring more features, become an even bigger part of your life! \n\n",
  "author": "theonion",
