  "title": "NATO’s Portugal: Cooperation Can Exist Without Political Uniformity",
  "content": "With the rise of China’s cryptocurrencies, the west once again feels threatened by an amicable initiative. Xinhua has had the honour of interviewing NATO’s own Portugal, providing us with some insight as to how the often arbitrary distinction is made between politics and economics.  \n\n\n----------\n\n\n(Xinhua) Good morning, Portugal. It is a pleasure to have you here. Generally speaking, how has China benefitted Portugal?\n\n>Since Portugal’s economic crisis beginning in 2010, China has made investments into various Portuguese business sectors including power grid operators, banks, insurance companies, and real estate. Through these Chinese investments, Portugal was able to alleviate the long term consequences of the economic crisis whilst simultaneously speeding up national economic redevelopment.\n\n(Xinhua) We heard the US delegation mention China’s national security threat. As a US ally, how have you been coping with this immense political pressure?\n\n> Our prime minister has made it clear on the international stage many times, that allies come first, and economic ventures always come second. We see the US as an ally, and we see our partnerships with China as solely economically driven.\n\n\n(Xinhua) Hungary stated the US has the ‘most comprehensive cyber network’ and noted that cybersecurity is used defensively in most nations. Do you think defensive use of cyber networks is justified?\n\n> Cybersecurity measures used defensively are beneficial to maintaining national security. By intercepting prospective attacks by malicious groups or other governments, a nation can prevent catastrophic damage on its web infrastructure and privacy from being achieved.\n\n(Xinhua) The US has a branch of the military that is the Cyber Command. Don’t you think this poses a greater threat to international security than individual companies in China?\n\n> It could be said that the Cyber Command poses a greater threat. However, Portugal has yet to invest in the research which might determine who is of greater risk.\n\n\n(Xinhua) France alleged that Huawei must send information to the government. As we all know, Huawei is an independent company that is not aligned with the Chinese government. What are your thoughts on these accusations?\n\n> China is an economic partner to Huawei and to China. Our delegation would not be able to comment on these accusations. However, the United States’ pre-decided stance on China’s technological ascendance warned that allowing a foreign nation, especially China, to have control over something as crucial to a country’s ability to function as its national telecommunication platform would be a critical mistake that could lead to an eventual state of dependence on China. Regardless, in the nature of a partnership, the economically-driven alliance between Portugal’s Altice and China’s Huawei will be a joint development of 5G services in our country, in which Huawei’s technologies will be employed, whilst Altice will continue to hold absolute control over the system. These foreign involvements with Portugal’s businesses have been and will continue to be controlled, preventing any threats to national security from arising.\n\n\n----------\n\n\nThe Xinhua News Agency would like to wholeheartedly express our gratitude towards Portugal’s valiant fight in NATO for truth and transparency. We also thank its commitment to openness through today’s interview.",
