  "title": "ILO: Japan’s Chinese Prison Probe Reignites Age-Old Sino-Japanese Feud",
  "content": "Just one week away from the 126th anniversary of the first Sino-Japanese War, tensions between the long-lived adversaries have once again reached their boiling point. During the International Labour Organization’s (ILO) fourth committee session, the delegation of Japan committed a diplomatic misstep, thus tripping the trigger wire of the East’s most explosive nation and allowing fellow delegates to experience the front lines of one of modernity’s worst feuds, reignited.\n\nImproving prison labour conditions was the topic at the top of the ILO’s action-packed agenda. Not even five minutes after roll call, Sweden, the United States of America (USA), the People’s Republic of China (PROC), and Japan, were submerged in a high stakes debate on the ethics of prison surveillance. \n\nDuring one particularly combative exchange of verbal warfare, Japan’s delegate chose to boldly go where no man of the committee had gone before and acknowledge the elephant (rather, the panda) in the room: China’s Uyghur genocide. The representative argued that the United Nations owed consideration to the marginalized group’s shockingly familiar circumstances, and this allusion to Europe’s failure in identifying the Holocaust’s concentration camps was very well received. In a brief following speech, the Japanese delegate made one final inflammatory comment, this time on Chinese prisons’ mandatory recitations of the Chinese national anthem, in response to which the PROC further deflected the blame onto the USA’s daily Pledge of Allegiance. \n\nJapan, however, was committed to seeing China pay. The representative urged allied nations to hold China accountable by collectivizing diplomatic clout in order to overpower the nation, with the end goal being to force China to welcome outside inspectors into their “re-education camps”\n\nWithout a hint of vitriol, the PROC’s delegate adamantly condemned the US’s alleged past Sinophobic statements, before subtly omitting the word “genocide” from all five of his speeches on the topic. China utilized this opportunity to promote its traditionally dogmatic justice system through strawmanning the prospect of a multifaceted treatment, citing prison simply as a place of punishment, not rehabilitation. At the end of the delegate’s informative speech, however, an ominous message was attached: the PROC “advised” Japan that it would do them well to keep their interests far outside of the Chinese state.\n\nMake no mistake, these words are no far cry from those that led to China’s split from not only Japan, but the USSR (Russia), as well. Further distancing between the two most powerful eastern nations does not bode well for extradition conditions, which Canada also takes a deep interest in.* Canadians, take care. In times of war, our allies have always proved steadfast. \n\n*See Michael Kovrig and Michael Spavor.\n",
