  "title": "US Senate: Blank Word Or Potential Solutions? A Battle To End Marginalization",
  "content": "*Present or quilty*? This was the alarming sound the Republicans echoed in the chamber of deception last night, as the senate finally opened a wound deep-rooted in American History: Black marginalization. \n\nAs senators acknowledge the issues faced by the minorities, little empathy was shown from the right, as the cloud of privilege simply imitated the same sentiment as the Jim Crow days reworded for the era. Notably absent, the majority leader Senator Schumer forfeited his given opening speech, pushing the senate to its feet. \n\nStriking arguments were presented by both sides, engulfing all possible solutions to the infrastructural issues plaguing America today, precisely the problems of zoning, education, and transportation. \n\nOn the topic of inappropriate zoning, senator McConnell presented a mediocre argument in that re-zoning projects may lead to a collapse in housing prices and the loss of neighbourhood identity. As a rebuttal, senator Sanders quoted recent rezoning projects’ success and the need for further attempts to solve the affordable housing crisis.\n\nTo tackle the issue of marginalization, the topic of education was also loosely discussed, as the Republicans promised little to no change. On this topic, Senator Sanders made key points on attempting to forge a dialogue with communities and that any money leaving federal pockets for education is being invested in America’s future, “not spent.”\n\nAs the debate elapsed, the senate fought one last debate on transportation, as two polar paths were paved for the senate to follow. The first path was set by the Democrats, as Senators wished for federal expenditure in the field, citing the failures of the private transport system set forth today. The Republicans, as always, blindly pushed against the democrat’s words setting the debate at a blocked road. In the face of the debate’s resumption tomorrow, a much-needed bill is expected, but the bill’s contents are up in the air.\n",
