  "title": "Crisis strikes the US Senate!",
  "content": "\n\nAfter taking a roll call lasting eleven minutes, Co-Director Joshua Dar Santos begins to explain the rules that the house will be following this session; his partnering Co-Director interjects occasionally.\n\nHeld in an atmosphere of great anticipation, the delegates can be seen eagerly absorbing the Co-Directors’ instructions and preparing sheets of note-taking paper.\n\nSpeaks further Co-Director Othman Mekhloufi, who introduces the details of the crisis—an illicit opioid sales crisis—and allows the senators to begin their debate.\n\nMinnesotan Senator Amy Klobuchar is the first to speak, urging the committee to increase regulations on opioid sales to “defer companies from seeking financial gain.”\n\nUnder the pressure of time to bring the criminals at hand to justice, Senator Whitehouse suggests that the Senate begins actively seeking the location of these criminals.\n\nNo points pass through the floor following this point.\n\nIn an attempt to induce urgency into these Senators, Co-Chair Alec Yang urges that all Senators—especially those who have yet to participate—to put forth their views on the pertinent issue.\n\n“Passing directives is a must,” says Yang.\n\nContinued silence, then a speech by Senator Collins from Maine.\n\nNewfound confidence flows through the conference as Senator Sinema makes a speech that gets her colleagues amped.\n\nGreat speeches fly back and forth from all sides of the Senate as a bipartisan solution begins to take shape.\n\nOnly time will tell the fate of the American opioid crisis of April 11, 2021.\n",
