  "content": "Coming into the ninth committee session of the conference, and the first one of the day, the UN Women scrambles to mitigate a crisis. A terrorist group by the name of ISIL is upset by actions taken by UN Women to free women from terrorist groups’ control. Having taken thirty thousand of girls and women hostage, ISIL plans to force these women into unwilling suicide bombings. Suicide bombings will happen every twenty minutes, in selected cities, and it is up to the delegates to take action to prevent the tragedy to occur in these cities. Many delegates have spoken and condemned the terrorist group, as it’s super important to condemn terrorist groups before taking action. UN Women comes up with suggestions in the favour of the safety of the hostages, such as economic sanctions, and gathering all women in one place to be defended, or evacuate all women to a rural area, all very feasible. New York City is to be the first target, though delegates are hard at work to protect the city. In the committee, a delegate finally speaks of an investigative operation, and suggests that delegates make an effort to find information on the terrorist group. Proposing slightly more feasible solutions, UN Women now suggests that countries take measures to screen and investigate any unknown people and missing women. Continuing to make plans of military intervention and force, the committee discusses how it may be difficult to employ this force, and makes suggestions such as an undercover operation. Now, delegates are discussing the benefits of public service announcements, and how women can be helped by an educational announcement. Good luck to the UN Women in their crisis. Overall, the committee has taken a productive start, we hope to bring you positive news soon.\n",
