  "title": "Injection Site Logistic Being Debated by US Senate",
  "content": "Republican Senator Cotton rejects ideas proposed by senators that injection sites must be opened. “We must be stopping this immediately… Republicans have been warning about shortcomings of injection sites all along,” he proclaims.\n\nKlobuchar responds with a doubtful view, skeptical of Cotton’s valid concerns: “I am making a directive to temporarily close injection sites…but once we know that it is safe, I suggest that we move to reopen them.”\n\nBut once again, pure American anti-drug values Alex Padilla seconds sentiments made by Cotton as well as other Republican Senators, pushing for injection sites to close to limit American heroin consumption.\n\nBut as soon as bipartisanship seemed to be on its last breath, Senator Rubio reminded others that a larger issue was also at hand: finding those responsible for distributing dangerous opioids around America.\n\nBut it seemed that others were not inclined to build off of Rubio’s remarks. Democratic Senator Gillibrand finds a way to keep debate in circles, insisting on discussing logistics surrounding injection sites. In this Fox News correspondent’s opinion, such a topic should be discussed after crisis events have long since passed; right now, I believe that Senators should instead focus on how drugs circulated around America. Senator Tom Cotton seems to agree, pushing senators away from discussing injection sites towards discussing crisis matters.\n",
