  "title": "Corporate Chemical Spill Sparks Outrage Amongst Cape Breton Nations (IAC)",
  "content": "Corporate Chemical Spill Sparks Outrage Amongst Cape Breton Nations (IAC)\n\nAt least three members of the Wagmatcook, Membertou, Eskasoni, and We’koqma’q nations have fallen seriously ill due to the contamination virus. Hospital beds have become less and less readily available due to the third wave of the COVID-19 pandemic: the public health authority is not prepared to handle a second crisis. \n\nSystemic racism in the medical field affects up to 78% of Indigenous Canadians (College of Family Physicians of Canada), and distrust for health professionals is often warranted. Moreover, racial disproportionalities (including higher risk of obesity, heart disease, diabetes, addiction, mental illness, and COVID-19) in Canadian healthcare mean that Indigenous individuals are far more likely to experience trauma due to poor compassion from health professionals. \n\nUnder Cermaq’s industry reign, this incident has been the first spill in the Norwegian fish farming corporation’s decades of community service. Nations such as the Wagmatcook Nation are frustrated due to the ecological destruction of the waterways in which they have been sustainably practicing cultural hunting practices for millenia. Indigenous Advisory Council (IAC) member Mumilaaq Qaqqaq is calling for an immediate criminal investigation into this matter. Promising justice to her supporters, Qaqqaq believes that this is an example of corporate racism. \n\nContaminated water is not only present in Cape Breton. Nations across all Canadian provinces have suffered under boiled water advisories, many of which are still in place, today. Generational trauma in Indigenous communities is of utmost priority to the IAC, and members are committed to granting Indigenous peoples their basic rights and freedoms (such as the right to clean water). Official resolutions passed by this committee will be reported upon by The Globe and Mail at the earliest possible convenience. \n",
