  "title": "IPC: Indigenous Peoples Face Different Discrimination, Ignored in Anti-Racism Work",
  "content": "Genocide is wrong. We all know that. It is wrong to discriminate. All Canadians are aware of this. Racism ended with closing the residential schools. While easy comforting, these common misconceptions are harmful. \n\nToday, Canada often hides behind a benevolent, polite facade. Too scared to face criticism, systemic racism is cleverly hidden. Canadians must understand that totem poles do not guarantee inclusion. Anti-Indigenous biases are everywhere, and oftentimes invisible to non-Natives. \n\nAccording to Canadian activists, the “support” given to Indigenous peoples is performative. These people do not need wasteful public projects, they need substantial mental healthcare. Tired of hearing false promises, our Indigenous people need action, not words and cheap lies. \n\nAccording to the First Nations Health Authority, Indigenous Canadians are struggling to maintain two identities. Duality in oneself is paramount to understanding the Indigenous cause: non-Natives must acknowledge and understand this. Even discussions of one’s homeland can be triggering: most Natives do not have homelands. The Indigenous Advisory Council strongly encourages all non-Native people to contemplate their settler privilege at least once each day. The fight against colonialism is not only that of Indigenous peoples, as Advisor Mumilaaq Qaqqaq pointed out. Racially privileged Canadians must use their power to dismantle the systems of oppression which unfairly benefit them. \n\nThe Globe and Mail acknowledges the unceded traditional Indigenous territories on which we live, learn, and fight for equality within Canadian journalism. \n",
