  "title": "Exclusive Interview with the Federation of Russia on the Conflicts in Balochistan ",
  "content": "The violence in Pakistan's largest province, Balochistan, continues. Numerous countries are gathering ideas but they keep failing to agree while time keeps running out. Russia, a famous world power known to be able to make or break a nation, is also involved in this debate. This afternoon, the New York Times got a couple of minutes to speak with the representative on some of the following topics that were brought up. \n\nFirstly, the committee spent lots of time expressing the importance of education in saving the nation of Balochistan. Russia trusts that education is crucial for any society, especially for Balochistan as the literacy rate still stands at 46%. Many other nations agree, but also believe that we should focus on electoral violence as it seems to be a bigger issue \n\nRussia recognizes these concerns but states how these just seem to be rumors. They aren’t willing to assume the rumours are true when there is no sort of evidence to back it up, no reports, videos or official allegations. Instead, Russia wants to go back to the root of the problem. They want to closely observe the issues and fully understand the people and problems before they start to blame anyone.   \n\nOnce they’ve gathered enough information, they want to improve the life of citizens in Balochistan. Now they’re aware this may  take time but they’re also ready to take it step by step. They heartily express that if people live in bad conditions, they are more likely to join organizations that promise them something better, this is how they get lured into terrorism. Terrorism is a huge isssue affecting this region so if they manage to stop it or at leats control it, it’ll already improve the nation by exceeding quantities. \n\nFellow governments involved in the debate, mentioned how they think it’ll be a good idea to host a conference only 2 weeks after an international aid organization is put in place. Russia strongly disagrees. They recognize how there is lots of distress between the nations and they believe how 2 weeks isn’t enough time to see how the changes put in place would play out.\n\nThe hope for change in this province is highly desired but so is the cooperation of international nations so they can save Balochistan once and for all. \n",
