  "title": "EXCLUSIVE: Anonymous Facebook Board Member Confides Evidence of Internal Threat Within Company",
  "content": "\nThe executives at Facebook currently face a dual threat. On one hand, it seems that the company is tackling some sort of data breach involving Swiss and Brazilian citizen data. Snap elections will soon occur in both nations, so this breach poses a significant problem to the integrity of these elections.\n\nHowever, the board faces a second threat: one from inside. A Fox News correspondent present at these meetings reveals that the executives currently suspect that there is a mole among them—somebody interfering with the attempted actions of the boards.\n\nA board member—who requested that we share the contents of their conversation with Fox without revealing their name—lists evidence they have seen of this collusion. They pointed out that a board member once “suggested that we shut down servers to protect data, and suddenly that ‘wasn’t feasible.’ It never went to a vote.”\n\nAnother suspicious occurrence he shared was a series of errors regarding lie detectors. “Somebody tried to get lie detectors to test staff members,” they say, “and for some reason the lie detectors ‘didn’t work.’” While attending meetings, the Fox News correspondent heard that the lie detectors did not function because they lacked batteries—a highly unusual occurrence in a multi-billion-dollar company.\n\nWhen asked if they suspected if Facebook Director Joyce Chen, Facebook Chair Tienlan Sun, or Facebook Chair Ellie Hwang were aiding the mole within the company, they state: “I don’t know. But several solutions have failed for questionable reasons.”\n\nIt is worth noting that Facebook Director Joyce Chen holds a tremendous amount of power in the company—more power than Mark Zuckerberg himself. She is also responsible for announcing all updates in the crisis, most of which are stated in a smooth, almost improvisational speech pattern, as if her very words could twist the course of the crisis.\n\nIt appears that the electoral situation in Brazil has gone downhill: candidates are pulling out left and right amidst fake news allegations. Facebook will need to take a hard stance against fake news—the same kind of news that stifled Donald Trump’s 2020 presidential campaign—and muscle through their internal issues.\n",
