  "title": "Opinion: DISEC is “Zesty” – Both Literally and Figuratively",
  "content": "(CNN) – Upon stepping into debate in DISEC, one quickly notices that the word “zest” is prominently used, both in speech and in the committee chat. From the DISEC Director stating “We appreciate your zestiness today, delegates”, Iraq responding with a “Thank you, most zesty director” and the statement being made that “UAE supports zestiness”, a question prominently appears before our minds: Is DISEC, in fact, zesty?\n\n(Opinion) – According to the Merriam-Webster dictionary, “zest” is a noun defined as \n“a piece of the peel of a citrus fruit (such as an orange or lemon) used as flavoring”, or alternately, “an enjoyable exciting quality” or “keen enjoyment”. The latter definitions surely seem plausible, as the delegates of Breakout Room 2 were extremely excited to the point where there were constantly three or more people loudly chattering over one another. The Director had to very loudly interrupt the delegates multiple times to restore decorum, and immediately at her departure, chaos once again ensued. The uncontrolled commotion of the lively delegates is surely the very picture of “keen enjoyment”.\n \nAs for “enjoyable exciting quality”, one need not look further than virtual backgrounds. Please proceed with caution, as some of the following descriptions may be disturbing to some viewers. From the destruction of the “cultural center” McDonalds, the mutilation of the much beloved Peppa Pig to Nicki Minaj being an icon, there are multiple depictions of “enjoyable exciting qualit[ies]”. \n \n \nNow one cannot dismiss the possibility that is a malapropism; perhaps this became an ingrained joke due to someone using the incorrect word. Perhaps an individual meant to say “hefty”, or “pesky”, or even “gillespie”, but in a moment of confusion stated “zesty”. Or this could very well be another case of glitchy audio quality hopelessly distorting words into oblivion. One can only speculate on the origins of the term.\n \nAs for the citrus fruit side of things, call to mind the phrase “fruitful debate”, and a slight connection could arguably be established. Citrus is a genus of flowering trees and shrubs in the rue family, Rutaceae. Some may say debate also “flowers”, and thus, an argument can theoretically be made for even that side of things. This theory is far-fetched, but undeniably, DISEC indeed has some “zesty” qualities.  \n",
