  "title": "US Senate: Curious Solutions Formed To Combat the Marginalization of Black Communities",
  "content": "In light of the political divide at the Capitol, the US Senate was in complete dismay as critical senators, including McConnell, Klobuchar, and Cruz, were all expelled from the committee, welcoming new members to power. This new era for the Senate is now met with a 50-50 Republican and Democrat divide, with all of the new senators acting as representatives of the Republican party.\n\nAs the debate resumed for the second last time, Senator Schumer recognized the perpetual economic issue faced by the Black community, denouncing the Republicans’ attempt to block all potential bills. In response, the new leader, minority Mike Carpo, wished for transportation and school choice, with empty promises of investments in these fields. \n\nFollowing this tense debate environment, the senate entered into a perpetual floor debate, with both sides introducing problems but missing accurate solutions. A key point brought up during the discussion from the Republicans was an educational tax credit for minority families, echoing the sounds of choice for education. Furthermore, discussion of down payment advancement saw tremendous support from left and right in the senate as they agreed that affordable housing is critical for advancements. \n\nSenator Bernie Sanders presented an incredible argument in the housing markets issue of systemic racism, quoting a study that showcased homes owned by white families in the same neighbourhood are worth more by as much as thirty percent. \n\nEnding the debate, minority leader Carpo pushed the need for a greater transportation infrastructure outlining the detriment caused by previous issues. The centuries-long battle that is national American politics fervently continues.\n",
