  "title": "Opinion: The Nordic Solution, and the West’s Struggle To Preserve Linguistic Minorities",
  "content": "Founded on colonisation and persecution, many western nations have adopted their own language(s) as the official one(s), disregarding those of oppressed, Indigenous groups. Apart from imperialism, the lack of Indigenous literature has led to this decline in its usage and function. Some nations in SOCHUM have proposed government education programs to teach minority languages at schools, whilst others have called for the use of technological databases to store these languages. \n\nHowever, there are two prime issues with these proposals. Firstly, not all non-minority-language speaking residences might be particularly keen on learning another language. Many nations like Canada already have numerous official languages, and an increasing number of people feel no need to learn more than one. Secondly, even if these minority languages are stored, it would serve no practical function in the long run as the number of speakers won’t necessarily increase nationally.\n\nTo combat this, nations, particularly Finland, have proposed enforcing laws regarding the persecution of linguistic minorities and special rights for its speakers. It is crucial for minority language speakers to better their socio-economic statuses to be in the position of influence to spread their respective language(s). Affirmative action to a mild extent would aid in this process. Nonetheless, it is crucial to note that the overuse of such initiatives would result in decreased quality of work. \n\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/2vDLRTH\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/hBPnrSw/Official-languages-Finland-2015.png\" alt=\"Official-languages-Finland-2015\" border=\"0\">\n\nChina has 56 ethnic groups, many of which have their own languages and dialects. It has done particularly well in preserving them through a combination of teaching Mandarin, English, and an ethnic group’s own language. Hence, individuals from marginalised groups would master widespread languages, offering them numerous job opportunities, whilst still preserving their own beautiful languages. \n\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/PZr6nnD\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/XZWCggY/China-linguistic-map.jpg\" alt=\"China-linguistic-map\" border=\"0\">",
